04597nam a22006975i 9781501707360DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t19981998nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97815017073607 a10.7591/97815017073602doi  a(DE-B1597)489611  a(OCoLC)1024061779  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 7aPOL0230002bisacsh04a338.9522211 aPempel, T. J., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aRegime Shift :bComparative Dynamics of the Japanese Political Economy /cT. J. Pempel. 1aIthaca, NY : bCornell University Press, c[1998] 4c©1998  a1 online resource (288 p.) :b2 tables, 2 charts/graphs  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aCornell Studies in Political Economy00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tPREFACE -- tINTRODUCTION -- tPART I. REGIMES-DIVERGENT APPROACHES TO POSTWAR STABILITY -- t1. Patterns of Political Economy: A Range of Regimes -- t2. Japan in the 1960s: Conservative Politics and Economic Growth -- t3. From Chaos to Cohesion: Formation of the Conservative Regime -- tPART II. REGIME SHIFTS-ADJUSTMENT, COLLAPSE, AND RECONSTRUCTION -- t4. Transition and Breakdown: An Era of Reconfigurations -- t5. Japan in the 1990s: Fragmented Politics and Economic Turmoil -- t6. Between Adjustment and Unraveling: Protection and Erosion of the Old Regime -- tConclusion: Regimes in a Changing World Economy -- tNOTES -- tINDEX0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe Liberal Democratic Party, which dominated postwar Japan, lost power in the early 1990s. During that same period, Japan's once stellar economy suffered stagnation and collapse. Now a well-known commentator on contemporary Japan traces the political dynamics of the country to determine the reasons for these changes and the extent to which its political and economic systems have been permanently altered.T. J. Pempel contrasts the political economy of Japan during two decades: the 1960s, when the nation experienced conservative political dominance and high growth, and the early 1990s, when the "bubble economy" collapsed and electoral politics changed. The different dynamics of the two periods indicate a regime shift in which the present political economy deviates profoundly from earlier forms. This shift has involved a transformation in socioeconomic alliances, political and economic institutions, and public policy profile, rendering Japanese politics far less predictable than in the past. Pempel weighs the Japanese case against comparative data from the United States, Great Britain, Sweden, and Italy to show how unusual Japan's political economy had been in the 1960s. Regime Shift suggests that Japan's present troubles are deeply rooted in the economy's earlier success. It is a much-anticipated work that offers an original framework for understanding the critical changes that have affected political and economic institutions in Japan.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aEconomic historyy1945-. 4aAsian Studies. 4aPolitical Science & Political History. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Political Economy.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Archive Pre-2000z978311053617140uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/978150170736040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781501707360423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781501707360.jpg  a978-3-11-053617-1  Cornell University Press Archive Pre-2000b2000  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK